eep in mind this is after I ran it through photoshop and shrunk it 50%.  Thanks for the help and if you want to CG it feel free.  I have a larger version if yah want but then again I might also re-ink it if I get some good crits.<br><br>[edit]<br><br>Ok, I think I kinda butchered it but It is an improvement from the last.  I still have a way to go so I need some help if I'm gunna re-ink it.  I think the stool kicks butt now though and I'm happy with the shoes but the hair and hands I went overboard on... they should have stayed thinner.  I would apreciate any feedback.  Tell me what I'm doing right and what's wrong. <p>-Joel<BR><BR><A HREF="http://www.baloneysammitch.8m.com"><IMG SRC="http://www.baloneysammitch.8m.com/banner.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Baloney Sammitch.com"></A></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ubaloneysammitch.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Baloney Sammitch</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://baloneysammitch.8m.com/me/icon.gif" BORDER=0> at: 2/22/02 5:31:15 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=albrecht>albrecht</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/20/02 8:07:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4813.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;Still Sitting Pretty With a Pistol in Hand&quot;</span><hr size=1> I really hate to say it, especially since you say you already caught hell...<br>but the lines. They are all exactly the same width. It makes what would be a VERY cool pic excrutiatingly bland.<br>Try doing thick lines first- on clothing and the outline.Then use thinner ones for bare skin and very minute details. Also, I find that curves look real good if the get thicker or thinner as they go. That's what I do, anyway. As for the steady hand- I myself still have a lot of problems with a shaky hand. Near as I can tell, practice makes perfect, as always.<br>You could also make like the pros and cheat by using various templates (you didn't think they got all those drawings picture perfect 100% freehand, didya? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=albrecht>albrecht</A> at: 2/20/02 8:10:13 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/udarkreaver66.showPublicProfile?language=EN>darkreaver66</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/22/02 9:12:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4813.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://liquid2k.com/darkreaver/images/avatar5.jpg  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;Still Sitting Pretty With a Pistol in Hand&quot; *</span><hr size=1> ...the lines look nice by the thigh and the shoes, and ome areas of the jacket...your line width variation is still inconsistent...I don't see anything going on in the face....aside from that, it looks okay.  <br><br>The position in general doesn't look all that attractive...with the stiff bending, and the ramrod straight neck and back.... <p><a href=http://darkreaver.freeservers.com> <img src="http://liquid2k.com/darkreaver/images/bannner2.jpg" BORDER=0> </a>  <img src="http://liquid2k.com/darkreaver/images/booicon2.gif" BORDER=0> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=neosolidus>NeoSolidus</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.fortunecity.com/petparade/milk/52/faye28.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/22/02 10:36:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4813.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.trilunar.com/dl/screen_01s.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;Still Sitting Pretty With a Pistol in Hand&quot; *</span><hr size=1> The idea is cool *a girl seated with a gun* but on a stool in that position doesnt make it realistic. A stool doesnt leave enough space to sit the way she is seated. Thats the reason it may look strange to some but dont really realize it. Instead of a stool why dont u try like an edge of something like the front of a car *her car* if she is as much as a mercenary or a cop or whatever. My point is to try other wider spaces than a stool it is very recomended. For the girl herself it is very good in proportions as far as it goes separating her from the stool. Try to add more expressions on her face like a bit *sexiness* if thats a word lol. And on the inkin part yes is true what u see on pros' work arent really all free hand they are retouched as well...remember we r all humans and we tend to shake some from time to time as we draw even pros!!! <br>so here ya go!!!<br><br><br>&quot;War is an excuse for looking for a way to die for your beliefs&quot;<br>~Neo Solidus~<br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/usunb4n3.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sunb4n3</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/23/02 8:57:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4813.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.student.hig.se/~kp01jhn/images/kitoko.mini2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;Still Sitting Pretty With a Pistol in Hand&quot; *</span><hr size=1> I like this picture. =)<br><br>I think the original was just fine for having no line variation (it could still have made a good base for a CG), but the new one certainly is 'livelier'.<br><br>I have some crits on the new lines, because (weighting lines in all honour) in some places the lines are just too thick. They are a bit shakey here 'n' there too, but this is something that I'm also suffering from. It's hard to give you good advice on inking, since there are so many ways to do it and I don't know what equipment you currently use...but I can explain how I do it and maybe you can get some ideas from that.<br><br>Some people use non-variable width pens for inking and just fill in the line variations. It's a very precise way of doing it, but also a bit on the slow side (you have to go over the lineart many times). This doesn't work very well for me (I tend to screw the lineart up), so I use variable linewidth tools. I've used a brush in the past, but now I've settled for a dip pen with steel nabs - it's a lot more forgiving than the brush and produces everything from very fine to very fat lines.<br><br>Key to inking with both the brush and the dip-pen is to keep them at a very upright angle and use quick, fluid strokes. The moment when you start hesitating or going too slow is when the lines become wiggly. This is why it's good to keep the pencil sketch untouched - lately I've been inking on very bright copies instead, so I can afford a few failures every now &amp; then. If you don't have access to a copying machine, you can scan the pencil sketch, make it very bright and print it on paper that will be good for inking. When you scan the lineart later, you can adjust the gamma settings of the scanner to filter away the lightgrey sketch.<br><br>Always use a ruler for straight things, such as barstool legs. An inking ruler (with an indented lower edge) is a must - if you use an ordinary one, chances are that the ink will bleed into the edge of the ruler and smear your art. It's not as important for very straight lines to have varied linewidth - rather, it's the other way around. Use line weighting for the curved lines and fixed linewidths for the straight ones. The only general exception to keep in mind is that the lines should be stronger on the side where there's supposed to be shadows.<br><br>Ah well, you probably know most of this already. I hope I was of any help. ^^''<br><br>/Sun'<br><br> <p><i>Yes, I was formerly known as 't4kum1'...</i></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=albrecht>albrecht</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/24/02 9:27:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4813.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;Still Sitting Pretty With a Pistol in Hand&quot; *</span><hr size=1> MUCH better. Now it's just a matter of practice <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ublarghd.showPublicProfile?language=EN>blarghd</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fresh Meat</span><br> <font color=#336699>(3/4/02 9:42:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4813.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> 